g.text: The Cognitive Control Hypothesis [1] states that the amount of information one’s working memory can hold simultaneously, known as cognitive load, is limited. To be processed effectively and safely, feedback must not place excessive demand upon one’s cognitive load.Multiple Resource Theory [2] suggests that people have different cognitive resources for processing different types of information, meaning some modalities can be used concurrently without reducing attentional capacity, yet others cannot. Whilst visual and auditory stimuli place demand on the same perceptual resources, haptic cues rely on different resources.This means haptic cues can be processed alongside visual cues, without exhausting the driver’s cognitive load. Therefore, visual-haptic feedback was selected for the proposed eco-feedback system. Long-term behaviour retention is achieved using social comparison of short and long-term performance, via the post-driving gamified app. Strategically-timed notifications are delivered to incentivise charging behaviours.Haptic pedal vibrationsif visual cues are not attended toDiffering vibrations for amber and red lightsLateral vibrations
